Date: 5 Jul 2000 13:31:32 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Africa News Service, 5 Jul 2000 10:57 AM EST [edited

Lassa fever has come to town
----------------------------
FREETOWN (Concord Times, 4 Jul 2000): Disease Control Manager, Dr. Haroun
Turay has confirmed that Lassa fever has claimed at least four lives. As
its name implies, Lassa is a disease that manifests itself through fever
and before you know it, bleeding sets in. A Lassa fever victim bleeds from
all openings of his or her body - the nose, ears, the anus and so on. The
incubation period of Lassa fever is between 3 to 21 days. The outbreak of
Lassa fever in [Freetown is a worrying development when you consider how
the disease is transmitted. Luckily perhaps, Dr. Turay says those rats
which bite people when they [the people are asleep and pass on the virus
through their [the rats' urine have not been seen in [Freetown. So we
[may be observing human-to-human transmission through body fluids. In
recent times, Lassa has killed 4 people of the same family; a doctor and 3
members of his family. [It is likely that there are more unreported deaths
in [Freetown: The Storm Newspaper of 1 Jul 2000 reported that 2 people had
died at the Approved School Camp and who knows where else. In most homes in
this very over-crowded city, the rat population far outnumbers the human
population, and rats are responsible for the spread of this disease.
However, in a family setting human-to-human transmission is a possibility.
Lassa fever is manifested [initially by fever, and fever is part of the
lives of Freetown residents. Self-medication for fever is a common
practice. A few chloroquine tablets plus paracetamol, or any anti-malarial
drug, is what most people take to get back online when they get fever. With
Lassa here with us, people should be more careful when diagnosing
themselves. Over the weekend, the Director General of Medical Services, Dr.
Sheku Tejan Kamara, expressed concern about the outbreak of Lassa fever in
[Freetown. Lassa fever is a disease that is localized in the Eastern part
of the country; i.e. Kenema, Segbwema, Panguma, Tongo and so on. Dr. Turay
says that measures are being taken to control the disease by effective
surveillance.
Lassa fever is another rebel that has invaded the city bringing into sharp
focus the little attention that the disease had probably received when it
was in the East. My wife asked me a "difficult" question the other day "Is
Lassa fever a new disease?" [My answer was that the presence of Lassa
fever is an indication of the "so-called" provincial marginalisation, [and
deficiencies in public health. Health Education talks on radio,
television, in mosques and churches should be given without delay. Also,
special attention should be given to those who have had contacts with Lassa
patients. [Rodent control measures should be stepped up. - Mod. CP.
Lastly, if you have fever today, don't just take few chloroquine tablets,
contact a doctor or visit a health centre.
[Byline: Sulaiman Momodu
